<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-192-038  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 192 038.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  Feb 12 1990 n577 p31(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Digital neurons mimic analog.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Johnson, R. Colin.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Neural Semiconductor Inc's digital neural network architecture(DNNA) bridges the gap between the continuous nature of neuralnetworks in the brain and the discrete nature of digital chiptechnology.andP;  The digital silicon chip set behaves as if it wereanalog.andP;  Digital hardware has only been able to simulatecontinuous activity because the state of a digital system'freezes' at each clock tick.andP;  Chief scientist Max StanfordTomlinson Jr.andP;  reasoned that digital design could use discretepulses of variable widths to represent continuous streams.andP;  Theactivation levels of neurons, the activity on a connection line,and the size of a given synaptic weight are represented by thepercentage of time their respective pulse streams are On.andP;  NeuralSemiconductor is one of only five vendors of commercial neuralnetwork microchips.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Neural Semiconductor Inc. (product development).andO;Topic:     Neural NetworksAnalog ComputersIntegrated Circuits.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Basic DNNA schematics. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>